[normal]18.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Our report on 
[normal]Defence and Cyber-Security
[normal] has formed part of our important analysis of the emerging threats to UK security. 
[normal]The 
[normal]inquiry explored whether the high profile given to the cyber-threat in the UK is m
[normal]atched by a coherent plan and chain of command in the event of a major cyber-attack on our national infrastructure or our national interests.
[normal]19.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We undertook a major report into 
[normal]Future Maritime Surveillance
[normal] in response to the decision announced in the 
[normal]SDSR 2010 to cancel the Nimrod MRA4 programme. Rather than revisit the cancellation of Nimrod, we  examined the implications of the decision for future maritime surveillance capabilities and assessed how the resultant capability gap would be managed. This 
[normal]included an assessment of the strategic requirements for military and non-military maritime surveillance capabilities, the various ways they are provided currently and in the future and how this would be incorporated into work on the next National Security
[normal] Strategy and next Strategic Defence and Security Review. A particular area of focus was cross-government cooperation, including the work of the Maritime Security Oversight Group and the National Maritime Information Centre.    
[normal]20.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We continue to place a high priority on our work in scrutinising the Ministry of Defe
[normal]nce’s Annual Report and Accounts, and the Department’s Estimates. The Report on 
[normal]the 
[normal]Ministry of Defence Annual Report and Accounts 2011-12 highlighted
[normal] the repeated qualification of the MoD Accounts; weak financial management information and the paucity of information provided in the Annual Report.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
